06541nam a22011535i 9780691219110DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212021nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020035229  a97806912191107 a10.1515/97806912191102doi  a(DE-B1597)576294  a(OCoLC)1245670754  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aHX238b.H37 2021 4aHX238b.H37 2021 7aHIS0370702bisacsh04a940.53/112223  aNQ 1050qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/128042:1 aHaslam, Jonathan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Spectre of War :bInternational Communism and the Origins of World War II /cJonathan Haslam. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (504 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Studies in International History and Politics ;v16300tFrontmatter -- tcontents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1 Crossroads to World Revolution, 1917–1920 -- t2 Europe at the Brink -- t3 Subverting Great Britain and Its Empire -- t4 The Manchurian Fiasco, 1931 -- t5 Stalin’s Gamble on German Nationalism -- t6 The Impact of Hitler -- t7 Italy Breaks Out -- t8 The Paradox of the Popular Front -- t9 Spain and the Schism of Europe -- t10 A United Front against Japan -- t11 The Appeasement of Germany, 1937–1939 -- t12 War, 1939–1940 -- t13 The Invasion of the Soviet Union -- tConclusions -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA bold new history showing that the fear of Communism was a major factor in the outbreak of World War IIThe Spectre of War looks at a subject we thought we knew—the roots of the Second World War—and upends our assumptions with a masterful new interpretation. Looking beyond traditional explanations based on diplomatic failures or military might, Jonathan Haslam explores the neglected thread connecting them all: the fear of Communism prevalent across continents during the interwar period. Marshalling an array of archival sources, including records from the Communist International, Haslam transforms our understanding of the deep-seated origins of World War II, its conflicts, and its legacy.Haslam offers a panoramic view of Europe and northeast Asia during the 1920s and 1930s, connecting fascism’s emergence with the impact of the 1917 Bolshevik Revolution. World War I had economically destabilized many nations, and the threat of Communist revolt loomed large in the ensuing social unrest. As Moscow supported Communist efforts in France, Spain, China, and beyond, opponents such as the British feared for the stability of their global empire, and viewed fascism as the only force standing between them and the Communist overthrow of the existing order. The appeasement and political misreading of Nazi Germany and fascist Italy that followed held back the spectre of rebellion—only to usher in the later advent of war.Illuminating ideological differences in the decades before World War II, and the continuous role of pre- and postwar Communism, The Spectre of War provides unprecedented context for one of the most momentous calamities of the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCommunismzEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aPropaganda, CommunistzEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial stratificationzEuropexHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Soviet relations.  aBarbarossa.  aBolshevism.  aCatholic Center Party.  aChamberlain.  aComintern.  aFascism.  aGreat Depression.  aHitler.  aJapan.  aManchuria.  aMussolini.  aNazi-Soviet Pact.  aNazi-Soviet pact.  aNazism.  aPoland.  aPopular Front.  aRussian revolution.  aSocial Democrats.  aSpan